## Bugs

- **A portal's foreign container isn't cleaned up when an ancestor holding the portal unmounts.** `unmount_vnode`'s `Element` arm (`src/diff.rs`) unconditionally passes `skip_remove: true` down to its children on the assumption that removing the parent element removes all its DOM descendants — true for ordinary children, but not for a `Portal`'s children, whose DOM actually lives in a separate container elsewhere in the page. Confirmed still present: the `Fragment | Portal` arm just forwards the same `skip_remove` it was given, with no special case for `Portal`. Effect/hook cleanup does still run correctly (see `unmounting_a_tree_with_a_portal_subtree_cleans_up_its_effects_and_content` in `tests/browser/portals.rs`, which deliberately only asserts the cleanup half and not DOM removal), but the portal's own DOM content is left behind in its target container. Not fixed here since the right fix (making `skip_remove` compute per-subtree, or having `Portal`'s unmount branch always force real removal for its children regardless of the flag passed down) touches shared unmount logic and deserves its own scrutiny/tests rather than a quick patch.
- **`NodeRef` goes stale after an unkeyed tag change.** `find_match` (`src/diff.rs`) matches unkeyed children by `(key, type_tag)`, and an `Element`'s `type_tag()` is its tag name, so e.g. a `div` → `span` swap doesn't diff as an in-place update — it's a remove-then-insert, run as two independent steps in `diff_children`: the new `<span>` mounts first (`ref_.set(Some(new_span))`), then the old, now-unmatched `<div>` is unmounted afterward, which unconditionally calls `ref_.set(None)`. Since the ref is the same `Rc`-shared `NodeRef` on both vnodes, the unmount step clobbers the mount step — a `<span>` is genuinely in the DOM, but the ref reads `None`. Documented (not fixed) by `node_ref_goes_stale_after_an_unkeyed_tag_change_bug` in `tests/browser/refs_dom.rs`, which intentionally asserts the current buggy behavior so a future fix (e.g. re-attaching refs after the unmount pass, or running unmounts before mounts) shows up as a test change. Left alone here: the fix touches diff/unmount ordering, not a quick patch.

## Test coverage gaps

- **`src/bindings.rs`**: `tests/browser/bindings.rs` and `tests/browser/bindings_gaps.rs` now cover most of the JsValue-marshalling layer (key coercion, ref shapes, state/reducer/memo/callback/id hooks through JS, context Provider/useContext shape, the `memo` double-free regression). Still open:
  - `js_use_effect`/`js_use_layout_effect` as called *from JS values* specifically (the underlying Rust hooks are covered in `tests/browser/hooks_scheduler.rs`, but not the `&Function`/cleanup marshalling layer on top).
  - `record_create_context_call`'s leak-count warning firing on the 2nd+ call (needs a console-spy hook the suite doesn't have yet).
  - `js_create_error_boundary`/`js_create_error_boundary_inner`: the re-entrancy guard (`in_progress`) blocking a nested synchronous re-entrant call, and `ResetOnDrop` clearing the guard after a panic.
  - `js_to_vnode`/`vnode_to_js`/`children_to_js`/`js_val_to_prop_val`/`props_to_js_object`: round-tripping every `PropVal` variant, array-as-fragment, and the `__mrVNode`/`__id` marker protocol directly (as opposed to incidentally, via every other test that renders something).
- **`src/scan.rs`** (`scan_tag_name_end`, `skip_js_string`, `skip_js_comment`, `find_matching_brace`) still has no dedicated unit-test file; it's only exercised indirectly through `jsx_test.rs`'s higher-level transpile assertions. Edge cases worth pinning down directly: unterminated strings/comments (should return `None`, not panic or scan past the end), nested braces inside a JS string literal inside a `{}` hole, and block vs. line comments abutting a tag boundary.

## Plans for extension

Things real React (or React Router) has that this project currently doesn't — one-liners, not scoped out further:

- No `useTransition`/`useDeferredValue` — everything renders through the same synchronous-priority flush path in `scheduler.rs`.
- No `Suspense`/lazy-loading story — `create_error_boundary` covers thrown errors but there's nothing for async/pending states.
- `forwardRef` exists (`src/bindings.rs`), but there's still no `useImperativeHandle` equivalent for exposing a custom imperative API from a component — `NodeRef` only ever points at a host element.
- No `useSyncExternalStore` — `use_context`'s subscribe/notify pattern in `context.rs` is basically a bespoke version of this for one specific case (context), but there's no general-purpose external-store hook.
- No `StrictMode`-style double-invoke-to-catch-impure-renders dev aid.
- `Link`'s `target`/`rel` handling isn't there — real `Link`/`NavLink` skip client-side navigation when `target !== "_self"` (e.g. `target="_blank"`); this implementation's `js_link` onclick doesn't check `target` at all, so a `<Link target="_blank">` would still hijack the click.
- No `<Link state={...}>` / `history.state` passthrough — `js_link`/`js_navigate` always push with `JsValue::NULL` as state, so `useLocation()`'s consumers can't receive router-passed state the way `location.state` does in react-router.

## Design/soundness notes

- **Raw-pointer hook dispatch (`hooks.rs`)**: `CURRENT_INST` is a `*mut ComponentInst` used via macros (`hooks_ref!`, `hooks_get_mut`, etc.) with `unsafe` blocks justified by "WASM is single-threaded, inst is valid for the render's duration." That's true today, but it's a hard invariant resting entirely on nothing calling back into JS in a way that could re-enter and mutate `hooks` while a `&mut` slot reference from `hooks_get_mut` (which is literally `&'static mut`, an aggressive lifetime cheat) is alive. The reentrant-render handling (`render_generation`) suggests the author is aware of this risk and has thought about it, but this is the single place I'd want the most scrutiny/fuzzing before trusting it in production, since the failure mode of getting it wrong is silent UB, not a panic.
- **`VNODE_STORE`**: raw `Box::into_raw`/`from_raw` was deliberately avoided in favor of an id-keyed map with idempotent removal — good instinct — but the "leak guard" only *warns* at 10,000 unconsumed entries via console; it doesn't actually reclaim anything. If a JS caller repeatedly constructs vnodes it never passes to render (e.g., a conditional branch that discards a built tree), this grows forever with only a log line to notice it.
- **Per-mount `Closure::forget()` calls compound if a component mounts/unmounts repeatedly.** `router.rs`'s `Router` popstate listener (via `use_effect_nodrop`) is correctly gated to run once *per mount* rather than per render — good. But `.forget()` still permanently leaks that closure, and it's not undone on unmount (no matching `remove_event_listener` for the popstate proxy). A `Router` that gets mounted and unmounted many times over an app's life (e.g. behind a modal, a tab switch, conditional rendering) leaks one popstate listener per cycle, same failure shape as the already-documented `createContext`-called-from-a-component-body case in `context.rs`. Not worth a big rewrite, but worth being aware it's not just a one-off case.
- **`Routes`' per-pattern thunks leak on every render, not just every mount.** `Routes` rebuilds and `.forget()`s a fresh `Closure` per matched route pattern on *every* render (needed so it picks up `children` changes rather than memoizing the route table forever). A `<Routes>` inside a frequently-re-rendering parent (e.g. one driven by a fast-ticking `setState` elsewhere in the tree) will leak proportionally faster than a mount-once memoization would. The right fix is a real memoization key derived from the route tree's *content* (e.g. path+pattern list, not raw `children` identity, since JSX children are freshly constructed vnode handles every render) rather than either extreme (never recompute vs. always recompute) — left as-is since that's a genuine design decision rather than an obvious bug fix.
- **`dangerouslySetInnerHTML`** and the general prop-setting path look correctly scoped (opt-in only, not the default path), and text nodes go through `create_text_node`, so ordinary text content isn't an XSS vector.
